---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const baseUrl = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
const withBase = (path) => `${baseUrl}${path.replace(/^\//, '')}`;
---
<BaseLayout title="Quick start · eunox" description="Run eunox-mcp in 60 seconds. Drop-in setup for Claude Desktop, Cursor, Windsurf, Go services, and any HTTP MCP client." activePage="quickstart">

    <section class="hero hero-compact">
        <div class="hero-eyebrow"><span class="dot"></span>Quick start</div>
        <h1>Ship a governed agent <em>in 60 seconds</em></h1>
        <p class="hero-sub">Three commands and a YAML file. The Go-based proxy runs locally, wraps any MCP server, and enforces policy before the upstream is ever contacted.</p>
        <div aria-live="polite" aria-atomic="true" id="copy-announce" class="sr-only"></div>
        <button class="install-snippet" aria-label="Copy install command">
            <span class="prompt" aria-hidden="true">$</span>
            <span class="cmd">eunox-mcp proxy --policy ./eunox.policy.yaml -- npx -y @modelcontextprotocol/server-filesystem /data</span>
            <span class="copy-btn" aria-hidden="true">copy</span>
        </button>
    </section>

    <nav class="breadcrumbs" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
        <a href={withBase('/')}>Home</a> &nbsp;›&nbsp; Quick start
    </nav>

    <main class="content-section">

        <div class="page-toc" aria-label="On this page">
            <h4>On this page</h4>
            <ul>
                <li><a href="#prereqs">Prerequisites</a></li>
                <li><a href="#step-1">Install</a></li>
                <li><a href="#step-2">Author a policy</a></li>
                <li><a href="#step-3">Validate the policy</a></li>
                <li><a href="#step-4">Run the proxy</a></li>
                <li><a href="#step-5">Try it from a host</a></li>
                <li><a href="#step-6">Inspect the audit log</a></li>
                <li><a href="#claude">Claude Desktop / Cursor / Windsurf</a></li>
                <li><a href="#http">HTTP transport · any MCP client</a></li>
                <li><a href="#go-sdk">Go SDK embedding</a></li>
                <li><a href="#next">Next steps</a></li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <h2 id="prereqs">Prerequisites</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>Go <strong>1.25+</strong> and the <code>eunox-mcp</code> binary on your <code>PATH</code></li>
            <li>An MCP host: <a href="https://www.anthropic.com/news/claude-desktop" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Claude Desktop</a>, <a href="https://cursor.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Cursor</a>, <a href="https://codeium.com/windsurf" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Windsurf</a>, or any agent that speaks <a href="https://spec.modelcontextprotocol.io/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">MCP</a></li>
            <li>An upstream MCP server you want to govern (for example <code>@modelcontextprotocol/server-filesystem</code>)</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout">
            <strong>Note.</strong> The <code>eunox-mcp</code> binary, while server-side services remain BSL-1.1. See <a href="https://github.com/edgeobs/eunox/blob/main/docs/tiers.md" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">docs/tiers.md</a> for the tier boundaries.
        </div>

        <h2 id="step-1">1. Install</h2>
        <p>Download the <code>eunox-mcp</code> binary from the <a href="https://github.com/edgeobs/eunox/releases/latest" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">latest GitHub release</a>, make it executable, and place it on your <code>PATH</code>:</p>
<pre><code># after downloading the binary for your platform
chmod +x ./eunox-mcp
mkdir -p ~/.local/bin
mv ./eunox-mcp ~/.local/bin/eunox-mcp
eunox-mcp --version</code></pre>

        <h2 id="step-2">2. Author a policy</h2>
        <p>A policy is a single YAML file describing which tools are allowed and the conditions on each call. Save the following as <code>eunox.policy.yaml</code>:</p>
<pre><code>agentId: filesystem-agent
name:    Filesystem Agent
version: 0.1.0

requiredCapabilities:
  - resource: read_file
    actions: [call]
    conditions:
      - type: allowedExtensions
        extensions: [".csv", ".json", ".txt", ".md"]
      - type: maxCalls
        count: 50
        windowSeconds: 60

  - resource: list_directory
    actions: [call]
</code></pre>
        <p>The schema is shared across the Go implementation, including the public packages under <code>pkg/capability</code> and <code>pkg/enforcement</code> — there is exactly one shape, no drift between the CLI and the rest of the system.</p>

        <h2 id="step-3">3. Validate the policy</h2>
<pre><code>eunox-mcp validate ./eunox.policy.yaml</code></pre>
        <p>Validation runs without contacting any server and rejects unknown condition types and malformed YAML up front.</p>

        <h2 id="step-4">4. Run the proxy</h2>
        <p>Wrap any MCP server with the proxy. Everything after <code>--</code> is the upstream command:</p>
<pre><code>eunox-mcp proxy   --policy ./eunox.policy.yaml   -- npx -y @modelcontextprotocol/server-filesystem /data
</code></pre>
        <p>The proxy speaks MCP on stdio in both directions and is transparent to clients.</p>

        <h2 id="step-5">5. Try it from a host</h2>
        <p>Point your MCP host (or any client) at the proxy command above. From <a href="#claude">Claude Desktop</a>, attempt to read <code>/data/keys.pem</code> — the proxy denies it before the upstream is contacted, and the agent receives a structured <code>CapabilityDenied</code> error.</p>

        <h2 id="step-6">6. Inspect the audit log</h2>
        <p>Every decision — allow or deny — is recorded as a signed OCSF API Activity event:</p>
<pre><code>tail -F ~/.eunox/audit.jsonl | jq</code></pre>
        <p>For aggregated denial counts, run:</p>
<pre><code>eunox-mcp stats</code></pre>
        <p>This prints an ASCII histogram grouped by condition type and denial code, including rotated log files.</p>

        <h2 id="claude">Claude Desktop / Cursor / Windsurf</h2>
        <p>Add the proxy as an <code>mcpServers</code> entry in <code>claude_desktop_config.json</code> (or the equivalent file for Cursor / Windsurf):</p>
<pre><code>{'{'}
  "mcpServers": {'{'}
    "filesystem-governed": {'{'}
      "command": "eunox-mcp",
      "args": [
        "proxy",
        "--policy", "/absolute/path/to/eunox.policy.yaml",
        "--",
        "npx", "-y", "@modelcontextprotocol/server-filesystem", "/data"
      ]
    {'}'}
  {'}'}
{'}'}</code></pre>
        <p>Without <code>--policy</code> the proxy is transparent — handy for capturing an audit trail before you write any rules.</p>

        <h2 id="http">HTTP transport · any MCP client</h2>
        <p>For agents that connect over HTTP rather than stdio, run the proxy as an HTTP server:</p>
<pre><code>eunox-mcp proxy   --transport http --port 7391   --policy ./eunox.policy.yaml   -- ./my-mcp-server
</code></pre>
        <p>Connect your client to <code>http://127.0.0.1:7391/mcp</code>. The same policy file works on both transports — and <code>ipRange</code> conditions become enforceable here.</p>

        <h2 id="go-sdk">Go SDK embedding</h2>
        <p>If your agent runtime already runs in Go and you do not want a separate proxy process, reuse the same manifest and enforcement primitives directly from the repository:</p>
        <ul>
            <li><a href="https://github.com/edgeobs/eunox/tree/main/pkg" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"><code>pkg/</code></a> — public Go packages for capabilities, enforcement, audit, identity, and support libraries.</li>
            <li><a href="https://github.com/edgeobs/eunox/blob/main/docs/agent-sdk.md" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"><code>docs/agent-sdk.md</code></a> — runtime SDK guidance for integrating hosted and local enforcement.</li>
            <li><a href="https://github.com/edgeobs/eunox/tree/main/internal/agentruntime" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"><code>internal/agentruntime/</code></a> — the Go runtime implementation used by the project itself.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Same YAML policy model, same conditions, same audit semantics — no Node.js package required.</p>

        <h2 id="next">Next steps</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>Drop in a ready-made policy from the <a href={withBase('/policies')}>reference policies</a> page.</li>
            <li>Browse the <a href={withBase('/features')}>full condition matrix</a> with worked demos for each.</li>
            <li>Read <a href={withBase('/how-it-works')}>how the proxy enforces policy</a> end-to-end.</li>
            <li>Explore the source on <a href="https://github.com/edgeobs/eunox" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">GitHub</a> — issues and PRs welcome.</li>
        </ul>
    </main>

</BaseLayout>
